(43, 4, 23, 50, 3, 3, 3, NULL, 'Worship in Spirit Connection', 'Both passages emphasize worshiping God in the spirit. John highlights true worshippers, while Philippians identifies those who worship God in the spirit.', 'theme', 0.629, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 23, 40, 15, 7, 9, 'worship the Father in spirit and in truth', 'Worship in Spirit and Truth', 'This connection highlights the contrast between true worship and mere lip service. Both passages emphasize the importance of genuine worship that comes from the heart rather than empty rituals.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 23, 43, 5, 25, 25, 'the hour cometh, and now is', 'Connection of Worship and Life', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''the hour'' indicating a significant moment for transformation. The first speaks of true worshippers, while the second refers to the dead hearing and living, suggesting a profound spiritual awakening.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 23, 48, 4, 6, 6, 'the Father seeketh such to worship him', 'Worship and Sonship Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worshiping the Father, as both passages emphasize a relationship with God. John 4:23 speaks of true worshippers, while Galatians 4:6 refers to believers as sons, indicating a familial bond with God.', 'theme', 0.496, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 23, 45, 8, 26, 26, 'worship the Father in spirit', 'Worship and Spirit''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of worshiping in spirit. John highlights true worshippers, while Romans speaks of the Spirit helping in prayer, suggesting a connection between authentic worship and the Spirit''s intercession.', 'theme', 0.46099999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 23, 65, 1, 20, 21, 'worship the Father in spirit and in truth', 'Worship and Spiritual Growth', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of spiritual engagement. John 4:23 speaks of worshipping in spirit and truth, while Jude 1:20 encourages building faith through prayer in the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.45399999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 23, 23, 29, 13, 13, 'worship the Father in spirit and in truth', 'Worship in Spirit and Truth', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of genuine worship. John highlights worshipping ''in spirit and in truth,'' while Isaiah critiques superficial worship that lacks heartfelt devotion.', 'theme', 0.419, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 24, 47, 3, 17, 17, 'God is a Spirit', 'Connection of Spirit and Worship', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Spirit in worship and freedom. John highlights the necessity of worshiping God in spirit, while 2 Corinthians connects the Lord with that Spirit, indicating that His presence brings liberty.', 'theme', 1.0, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 24, 40, 15, 8, 9, 'worship him in spirit and in truth', 'Worship in Spirit and Truth', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of genuine worship. John 4:24 highlights worshiping God in spirit and truth, while Matthew 15:8-9 critiques worship that lacks true devotion of the heart.', 'theme', 0.8319999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 24, 50, 3, 3, 3, 'worship him in spirit', 'Worship in Spirit Connection', 'Both passages emphasize worshiping God in the spirit. John highlights the necessity of worshiping in spirit and truth, while Philippians identifies true worshipers as those who worship God in the spirit.', 'theme', 0.8180000000000001, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 24, 19, 51, 17, 17, 'spirit', 'Worship and Broken Spirit Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of a sincere inner disposition in worship. John highlights worshiping ''in spirit,'' while Psalms speaks of a ''broken spirit'' as a true sacrifice to God.', 'theme', 0.6359999999999999, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 24, 23, 57, 15, 15, 'worship him in spirit', 'Worship and Humility Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of a humble spirit in worship. John highlights worshiping in spirit and truth, while Isaiah speaks of dwelling with the humble and contrite. This connection highlights the necessity of inner sincerity in approaching God.', 'theme', 0.587, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 24, 9, 16, 7, 7, 'worship him in spirit and in truth', 'Worship and Inner Truth', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of inner qualities over outward appearances. John 4:24 highlights worshiping in spirit and truth, while 1 Samuel 16:7 states that the Lord looks on the heart, not the outward appearance.', 'theme', 0.566, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 24, 54, 1, 17, 17, 'God is a Spirit', 'Worshiping the Invisible God', 'This connection highlights the nature of God as both spirit and invisible. Both passages emphasize the importance of recognizing God''s spiritual essence and eternal nature in worship.', 'theme', 0.496, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 25, 43, 1, 49, 49, 'Messias cometh, which is called Christ', 'Recognition of the Messiah', 'This connection highlights the recognition of Jesus as the Messiah. The woman at the well anticipates the coming of the Messiah, while Nathanael directly acknowledges Jesus as the Son of God and King of Israel.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 25, 27, 9, 24, 26, 'Messias cometh, which is called Christ', 'Connection Between Messiah References', 'Both passages emphasize the coming of the Messiah. In John 4:25, the woman speaks of the Messiah who will reveal all things, while Daniel 9:25 refers to the Messiah the Prince, indicating a significant role in God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 25, 40, 1, 16, 16, NULL, 'Connection of Christ''s Identity', 'This connection highlights the identification of Jesus as the Christ. The woman in John acknowledges the coming Messiah, while Matthew explicitly names Jesus as Christ.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 25, 43, 1, 41, 42, NULL, 'Connection of Messias and Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as the Messias, which is interpreted as Christ. The woman in John 4:25 anticipates the coming of the Messias, while John 1:41-42 declares that he has been found.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 25, 5, 18, 15, 18, 'when he is come, he will tell us all things', 'Connection of Prophetic Expectation', 'Both passages emphasize the coming of a Prophet who will reveal God''s truth. The woman in John anticipates the Messiah who will ''tell us all things,'' paralleling the promise in Deuteronomy of a Prophet who will speak God''s words.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 26, 43, 8, 24, 24, NULL, 'Connection of Identity in Christ', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Jesus as ''I am he.'' The first passage reveals Jesus'' self-identification to the Samaritan woman, while the second stresses the necessity of believing in this identity for salvation.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 26, 41, 14, 61, 62, 'I that speak unto thee am he', 'Identity of Jesus as Messiah', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' self-identification as the Messiah in both passages. In John 4:26, Jesus reveals his identity to the Samaritan woman, while in Mark 14:62, he affirms it before the high priest.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 26, 43, 9, 35, 37, 'I that speak unto thee am he', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Identity', 'This connection highlights the revelation of Jesus'' identity in both passages. In John 4:26, Jesus declares, ''I that speak unto thee am he,'' while in John 9:37, he states, ''Thou hast both seen him, and it is he that talketh with thee.''', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 26, 45, 10, 20, 21, 'I that speak unto thee am he', 'Revelation of Identity', 'This connection highlights the theme of revelation, as Jesus declares his identity to the Samaritan woman, paralleling God''s revelation to those who did not seek Him in Romans. Both passages emphasize the unexpected nature of divine encounters with those outside traditional boundaries.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 26, 40, 26, 63, 64, 'I that speak unto thee am he', 'Identity of Jesus as Messiah', 'This connection highlights Jesus'' self-identification as the Messiah in both passages. In John 4:26, Jesus declares, ''I that speak unto thee am he,'' while in Matthew 26:64, he affirms his identity as ''the Christ, the Son of God.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 26, 42, 13, 30, 30, NULL, 'Last and First Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of reversal in God''s kingdom. Both passages emphasize the unexpected nature of who is recognized and valued, with Jesus declaring himself as the Messiah and the notion that the last will be first.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 26, 40, 16, 20, 20, 'I that speak unto thee am he', 'Identity of Jesus Revealed', 'This connection highlights the revelation of Jesus'' identity. In John 4:26, Jesus explicitly states, ''I that speak unto thee am he,'' affirming his role as the Messiah, while Matthew 16:20 emphasizes the instruction to keep this identity concealed.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 27, 42, 7, 39, 39, 'What seekest thou? or, Why talkest thou with her?', 'Reactions to Jesus and Sinners', 'Both passages emphasize the disciples'' and Pharisee''s astonishment at Jesus'' interactions with women labeled as sinners. This connection highlights societal judgments regarding sinfulness and the unexpected nature of Jesus'' acceptance.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 27, 43, 4, 8, 9, 'What seekest thou? or, Why talkest thou with her?', 'Disciples'' Reaction to Jesus'' Actions', 'This connection highlights the disciples'' surprise at Jesus talking with a Samaritan woman, as indicated in both passages. The woman''s question about Jesus asking for a drink underscores the cultural barriers that the disciples also seem to recognize.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 28, 43, 4, 7, 7, NULL, 'Interaction with the Samaritan Woman', 'Both passages emphasize the encounter between Jesus and the Samaritan woman. The woman''s action of leaving her waterpot in John 4:28 signifies a transformation that begins with her initial meeting with Jesus in John 4:7.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(43, 4, 28, 42, 24, 33, 33, 'went her way into the city', 'Urgency in Sharing News', 'This connection highlights the urgency of both women and men in sharing significant news. The woman in John leaves her waterpot to tell the men in the city, while the disciples in Luke rise up to return to Jerusalem immediately.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
